# /etc/sudoers.d/blackbox-system
# Generated by BlackBox install.sh — DO NOT EDIT BY HAND.
#
# Grants the BlackBox service user passwordless sudo for a TIGHTLY BOUNDED
# set of system operations. The grant itself is the security perimeter:
# any prompt-injection RCE through an MCP tool can ONLY invoke commands
# listed here. The dispatch helpers (/usr/local/sbin/blackbox-{apt-install,
# write-systemd}) add a second layer of validation but the perimeter is
# already this file.
#
# History:
#   - E1   : initial Tailscale wizard grants
#   - E2   : NoNewPrivileges=false in unit (required for sudo escalation
#            despite the bounded grants; container-style hardening alone)
#   - E22a : service-restart + journalctl grants for portal restart+logs
#   - T5   : renamed -tailscale → -system; added update-pipeline grants
#            via /usr/local/sbin/blackbox-* dispatch helpers (T2). Audit
#            C3 + C4 ruled out wildcard `apt-get install -y *` and
#            `tee /etc/sudoers.d/*` as priv-esc primitives.

# ── Tailscale wizard actuator (E1) ──────────────────────────────────────
REAL_USER_PLACEHOLDER ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/apt-get install -y tailscale
REAL_USER_PLACEHOLDER ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/tailscale up --accept-dns=true --hostname=*
REAL_USER_PLACEHOLDER ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/tailscale set --accept-dns=true
REAL_USER_PLACEHOLDER ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/tailscale cert *
REAL_USER_PLACEHOLDER ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/tailscale serve --bg --https=443 9091
REAL_USER_PLACEHOLDER ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/tailscale serve status --json
REAL_USER_PLACEHOLDER ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/tailscale serve reset
REAL_USER_PLACEHOLDER ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/tailscale logout
REAL_USER_PLACEHOLDER ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/systemctl start tailscaled
REAL_USER_PLACEHOLDER ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/systemctl enable tailscaled

# ── Service control + logs (E22a) ───────────────────────────────────────
REAL_USER_PLACEHOLDER ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/systemctl restart blackbox.service
REAL_USER_PLACEHOLDER ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/journalctl -u blackbox.service *

# ── Update pipeline (T5) ────────────────────────────────────────────────
# These are the ONLY grants needed for the update pipeline. Each helper
# script validates its arguments before doing anything destructive:
#
#   blackbox-apt-install <pkg>
#     - regex-checks <pkg> against ^[a-z0-9.+-]+$
#     - verifies <pkg> is in Scripts/onboarding/system-packages.txt allowlist
#     - then: apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends <pkg>
#
#   blackbox-write-systemd <target_kind> <source_file>
#     - target_kind whitelisted to: unit | override | cli-agent-overrides | sudoers-system
#     - destination is HARDCODED per target_kind (caller cannot pick path)
#     - sudoers-* targets validated by `visudo -c` BEFORE copy
#     - systemd targets trigger daemon-reload after write
#
# A prompt-injection RCE cannot abuse these to install arbitrary packages,
# write arbitrary sudoers rules, or escalate beyond the dispatcher's
# narrow purpose. That's the design intent — the helpers ARE the policy.
REAL_USER_PLACEHOLDER ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/local/sbin/blackbox-apt-install *
REAL_USER_PLACEHOLDER ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/local/sbin/blackbox-write-systemd *

# ── Update-pipeline install.sh re-run (Brandon 2026-05-24) ──────────────
# Bounded to the exact BLACKBOX_ROOT path so an attacker who can write
# another bash script can't use this grant against arbitrary targets.
# install.sh itself is git-tracked and changes only on update; an attacker
# with write access to install.sh could already trigger root via this on
# the next Portal update regardless, so the grant doesn't widen the actual
# threat model. Avoids the "scary FAILED message" UX (cecc3c1) by letting
# the runner's `sudo -n bash install.sh` actually succeed for the systemd
# regen phase.
REAL_USER_PLACEHOLDER ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/bash BLACKBOX_ROOT_PLACEHOLDER/Scripts/install.sh

# ── Zellij CLI Agent (Track A T4, audit C5) ─────────────────────────────
# Grants required by the Zellij rewrite of the CLI Agent terminal stack.
# Plan: docs/plans/2026-05-24-zellij-cli-agent-rewrite.md (Track A).
#
# Why three grants and not just `restart`:
#   - `systemctl restart zellij-web.service` — normal lifecycle (rotate
#     binary, recover from a hung session, post-update bounce).
#   - `systemctl daemon-reload` — REQUIRED whenever the unit file content
#     on disk changes (e.g. update pipeline writes a new
#     zellij-web.service via blackbox-write-systemd). `restart` alone does
#     NOT re-read the unit; systemd will keep running the old definition
#     until daemon-reload. These are separate sudo verbs, hence two grants.
#     NOTE: this grant is general-purpose — any future unit added via
#     blackbox-write-systemd benefits from it; do NOT duplicate this rule
#     in future sections (e.g. a hypothetical worker.service grant block).
#   - `/usr/local/sbin/blackbox-install-zellij-binary *` — dispatcher
#     script (written by Track A T4.5) that drops the pinned zellij
#     binary into /usr/local/bin/. The orchestrator namespace runs with
#     ProtectSystem=strict (see MEMORY: protectsystem_strict_blast_radius),
#     so writes to /usr/local/bin/ are blocked even via sudo from inside
#     the service. The dispatcher does the bounded root operation,
#     mirroring blackbox-write-systemd + blackbox-apt-install: it
#     validates the version arg against an allowlist, verifies the
#     downloaded artifact's checksum, then performs the atomic install.
#     The wildcard `*` follows the same pattern as the existing
#     blackbox-apt-install / blackbox-write-systemd grants — argument
#     validation lives inside the helper, not in the sudoers rule.
REAL_USER_PLACEHOLDER ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/systemctl restart zellij-web.service
REAL_USER_PLACEHOLDER ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/systemctl daemon-reload
REAL_USER_PLACEHOLDER ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/local/sbin/blackbox-install-zellij-binary *
